				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">Cost is definitely a huge thing, if not the biggest thing when it comes to the actual product and production. I am a jack-of-all-trades who needs a lot of graphics for this project, so something like the MMC3 is ideal, and I don't have to pay an artist because I'll be doing it myself. But discrete parts are super cheap (like 20 cents per chip) and if all you need is 8 kb of CHR ROM or something then using MMC3 &quot;just because&quot; is just throwing your money away. Not only that, but when I was working with the UNROM format, I learned a lot while trying to tackle the various issues I was having with its limits, which of course is invaluable.<br /><br />The main reason I am developing a new game for the NES is BECAUSE of the limitations. I find they force me to think in ways that I otherwise would never have given the virtually unlimited freedom of, say, PC development or Flash/Air. The constraints are what drive me to push the limits of the console as well as my own limits of creativity and problem solving.<br /><br />Either way, at the end of the day, Super Mario Bros is NROM. Enough said.  <img src="./images/smilies/icon_cool.gif" alt="8-)" title="Cool" /></div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

